                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 339</seg>
                </opener>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>For documentation on the Netherlands defense effort and attitude toward a German
                    contribution to the defense of Western Europe, see <ref
                        target="frus1951v03p1#pg_1">volume <hi rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, Part 1,
                        pages 1</ref> ff. and <ref target="frus1951v03p1#pg_990">990</ref> ff. For
                    documentation on the interest of the Netherlands in the economic and political
                    integration of Western Europe, see Documents 1 ff. herein. For documentation on
                    the interest of the Netherlands in the control of exports to Eastern Europe and
                    the Soviet Union, see volume I, pages 993 ff. An exchange of correspondence
                    between Queen Juliana and President <persName corresp="#p_THS1"
                        >Truman</persName> on the problems of refugee relief in Europe is printed in
                    Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, October 8 and 29, 1951,
                    pages 572 and 701. For documentation regarding United States policy on the
                    question of European tariff disparities, raised by the Netherlands in the
                    Torquay tariff negotiating conference, 1950–1951, see volume I, pages 319
                    ff.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
